Stop duplicating localStorage and sessionStorage logic. Learn how to build a unified, SSR-safe, and fully type-safe browser storage layer using abstract classes.
In modern web development, persistent client-side state is unavoidable. Whether it is caching user preferences, preserving authentication tokens, or saving temporary wizard forms, we constantly reach for browser features like localStorage and sessionStorage.
However, in an enterprise Angular application — especially one running Server-Side Rendering (SSR) or Hydration — raw storage access becomes dangerous.
If your code evaluates window.localStorage on the server during pre-rendering, Node.js throws a reference error and crashes the execution pipeline. To survive, developers often litter their components and services with repetitive isPlatformBrowser guards and manual JSON.parse or JSON.stringify try-catch blocks. Even worse, they write two nearly identical services: one for local storage and one for session storage, violating the DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle.
The clean engineering solution is to build a type-safe, environment-aware Storage Abstraction Layer using the Template Method Pattern.
The Architecture: Template-Driven Storage
By building an abstract core class, we centralize platform checking, serialization safety, and fallbacks. The concrete implementations (LocalStorage and SessionStorage) then become incredibly lightweight, only providing their respective storage engines.

• The Core Infrastructure (browser-storage.ts)
import { inject, PLATFORM_ID } from '@angular/core';
import { isPlatformBrowser } from '@angular/common';export abstract class BrowserStorage {
protected readonly _platformId = inject(PLATFORM_ID);
protected readonly _isBrowser = isPlatformBrowser(this._platformId);
protected abstract get storage(): Storage | null;
get<T>(key: string, fallBack: T | null = null): T | null {
if (!this._isBrowser) return fallBack;
try {
const raw = this.storage?.getItem(key);
return raw === null || raw === undefined ? fallBack : (JSON.parse(raw) as T);
} catch (error) {
return fallBack;
}
}
set<T>(key: string, value: T): boolean {
if (!this._isBrowser) return false;
try {
this.storage?.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
return true;
} catch (err) {
console.error(`[Storage] Failed to write "${key}"`, err);
return false;
}
}
remove(key: string): void {
if (!this._isBrowser) return;
this.storage?.removeItem(key);
}
clear(): void {
if (!this._isBrowser) return;
this.storage?.clear();
}
has(key: string): boolean {
if (!this._isBrowser) return false;
return this.storage?.getItem(key) != null;
}
}
2. The Concrete Implementations (local-storage.service.ts & session-storage.service.ts)
Thanks to our abstract base, extending this functionality to explicit browser providers requires zero boilerplate.
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserStorage } from './browser-storage';@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class LocalStorage extends BrowserStorage {
protected override get storage(): Storage | null {
return this._isBrowser ? window.localStorage : null;
}
}
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserStorage } from './browser-storage';@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class SessionStorage extends BrowserStorage {
protected override get storage(): Storage | null {
return this._isBrowser ? window.sessionStorage : null;
}
}
Architectural Deep Dive
1. The Power of the Template Method Pattern
Instead of copy-pasting the exact same serialization logic, BrowserStorage acts as a template controller. It exposes public API endpoints (get, set, has) that orchestrate the pipeline workflow, while delegating the specific resource selection down to subclasses via the abstract storage getter.
2. Native Generic Serialization (<T>)
A native browser storage engine handles strings only. Forcing engineers to call JSON.stringify manually on every write degrades developer experience (DX). Your custom abstraction handles serialization implicitly at the boundary layer:
// Completely type-safe read and write operations
this._localStorage.set('user_profile', { id: 1, role: 'ADMIN' });
const profile = this._localStorage.get<UserProfile>('user_profile');3. Graceful SSR Fail-safes
When running on the server, _isBrowser evaluates to false. Instead of breaking or throwing unexpected exceptions, write operations gracefully short-circuit, and queries immediately return your typed fallBack values. This maintains strict hydration integrity.
Conclusion
The sign of an elegant software architecture is its ability to take a messy, platform-dependent Web API and wrap it in a highly clean, developer-friendly interface. By leveraging object-oriented inheritance alongside modern Angular injection patterns, you eliminate duplicate files, secure your SSR rendering pipeline, and give your engineering team an intuitive, type-safe API.
